snippet.title: Outdoor Play | Funny Kids | Vowels | Dancing | Jumping - SUPER RUDY KIDS
snippet.description:
Playing outdoors promotes well-being and physical development.

Kids are naturally drawn to playing outside and there are numerous benefits of outdoor play: 
- it allows them to explore their environment
- develop muscle strength and coordination
- gain self-confidence. 

Playing actively outdoors also increases:
- flexibility
- fine and gross motor skills
- is related to the development of a wide variety of physical skills, including those involved in sports.

Time for outdoor play is diminishing, contributing to more sedentary lifestyles, disconnected from the natural world. 

Recognizing the importance of outdoor play is essential for young children's healthy growth.

This video highlight the role families in creating quality outdoor play opportunities.

NURSERY RHYMES - WHY ARE SO IMPORTANT FOR OUR CHILD’S DEVELOPMENT?

Reason #1: It Improves their attention span
Reason #2: It aids in their language development
Reason #3: It improves their social skills

snippet.description:
Chris pretend play running around the different parts of the outdoor playground fun for kids. He dances to the 5 little monkeys song, and ends up on the beach counting 1-10 and splashing in the sea. Join him on his amazing fun times.

Q: What is pretend play and why is it important in imaginative play in child development?

A: Fantasy and dramatic play grow children's brains. …pretend play is a healthy part of every child's social, emotional, and cognitive development and should not be feared by parents or educators. Pretend play allows children to learn about their dislikes and likes, and aids them in experimenting in role play and to think about what they’ve observed. This is a child's way to go on to work out new life issues, for example what they find scary and confusing. Children develop important complex social and higher order thinking skills, it requires further thinking and planning as well as balancing their own ideas with others also cultivating social and emotional intelligence. 


Q: What age does pretend play start?

A: The act of pretending is believed to be inbuilt because it occurs universally and begins promptly between the ages of 18-24 months.
*As advised by Wikipedia, link below: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Make_believe#Critical_period


Q: What are pretend play examples and ideas?

A: Playing with an object as if that object is alive; some examples of pretend play include being superheroes, playing ‘mummies and daddies’, playing shopping, dress‐ups, playing flying to the moon, tea‐parties, playing trucks in the sandpit and playing with dolls and teddies to name a few. 
*As noted by Karen Stagnitti in the link below:
https://www.learntoplayevents.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/What-is-Pretend-Play-Full.pdf
